Description.val:
The F/A-18E/F Naval Strike Fighter is a twin-engine, mid-wing, multi-mission tactical aircraft. F/A-18E/F can be missionized through selected use of external equipment to accomplish specific fighter or attack missions. This
capability allows the Operational Commander more flexibility in employing his tactical aircraft in a dynamic scenario. The primary design mission for the F/A-18E/F is a strike fighter which includes the traditional applications,
such as fighter escort and fleet air defense, combined with the attack applications, such as interdiction and close air support. Since the same airframe systems are used on attack missions as well as fighter missions, excellent fighter
and self defense capability is retained.

Justification.val: There are no F/A-18E/F aircraft programmed in FY14.  Funding in F/A-18E/F is programmed to support the manufacture, acceptance and delivery of tasks common for F/A-18E/F and EA-18G. As per OSD direction, Production Engineering Support (PES) and Integrated Logistics Support (ILS) funded efforts that are common to both F/A-18E/F and EA-18G aircraft are budgeted in the F/A-18E/F APN-1 budget. These two support are not proportional to the number of aircraft being procured. This is not duplicative to support funding in PES and ILS of the EA-18G budget.

ProcQuantity.@footnote: FY 2010 Aircraft deliveries: 17 F/A-18E and 1 F/A-18F.
FY11 Aircraft deliveries: 22 F/A-18E and 9 F/A-18F.
FY12 Aircraft deliveries: 22 F/A-18E and 6 F/A-18F.
FY13 Aircraft deliveries: 23 F/A-18E and 3 F/A-18F.

Name.@footnote: CFE Electronics: Airframe (line 1) and CFE (line 2) are combined as one negotiated average unit price under MYPIII.  The negotiated distribution of the unit cost dollar amount between Budget Lines 1 and 2 varies annually for the MYPIII period. The EA-18G has a similarly varying pricing structure.  This variance in percentage contributes to the differences in unit cost.

GFE Electronics: The increase to the FY13 GFE cost element is attributable to the inclusion of costs associated with material cost increases, obsolescence issues and unit cost variations to manufacture GFE components.   FY13 Pricing for multiple items included new pricing estimates based on additional data, contracts figures, and inputs from NAVICP data.  The culmination of these various inputs led to an expected increase in unit cost that was over the OSD escalation rate.
Engines/Eng Acc: The increase to the FY13 cost element is attributable to the industry escalation forecasts.
Armament: The increase to the FY13 Armament cost element is attributable to a budget reduction in FY12 that caused the unit price of the gun systems to increase significantly between FY12 and FY13.
Airframe PGSE: The increase to the FY13 Airframe PGSE cost element reflects funding for equipment needed to stand up two squadrons.
Engine PGSE: The increase to the FY13 Engine PGSE cost element is for the Generator Convertor Unit (GCU) Silicon Control Rectifier (SCR) Dynamic Counter Tester (DCT).

Avionics PGSE: The increase to the FY13 Avionics PGSE cost element is for V3 Depot Standup Specialized Test Equipment, V3 Depot Standup Antenna Range and Tactical Aircraft Moving Map Capability (TAMMAC) E/F PC Memory Card International Association (PCMCIA) map cards.
Peculiar Training Equipment: The increase to the FY13 Peculiar Training Equipment cost element is for Tactical Operational Flight Trainers (TOFTs) software updates to the H10 software tape.

Publications and Technical Equipment: The increase to the FY13 cost element is for Interactive Electronic Technical Manuals (IETM), F/A-18 Automated Maintenance Environment (FAME), Information Assurance (IA), technical publications for the Organizational and Intermediate (O & I) levels, Engineering Change Proposals (ECPs) and Rapid Action Minor Engineering Changes (RAMEC).   These publications are the source of technical data for the F/A-18E/F & EA-18G.

Production Engineering Support (PES): The FY14 funding in the PES cost element supports delivery of the previously programmed F/A-18 E/F procurements.  This is not duplicative of Production Engineering funding in the EA-18G APN-1 budget.

Integrated Logistics Support (ILS): The FY14 funding in the ILS cost element supports delivery of the previously programmed F/A-18 E/F procurements.  This is not duplicative of Integrated Logistics Support funding in the EA-18G APN-1 budget.
